library(dplyr)
radonDataset <- read.table("srrs2.dat", header = T, sep = ",")
radonDataset <- dplyr::select(radonDataset, idnum, state, county, cntyfips, activity) %>%
                filter(state == "MN") %>%
                dplyr::select(-state) %>%
                mutate(county = trimws(county),
                       activity = log(ifelse(activity == 0, .1, activity))) %>%
                rename(logRadon = activity)

Model with No Predictors

Complete-pooling Regression

\[y_{i} = \alpha + \epsilon_{i}\] \[\epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2)\]

  • \(y_i\) is the logarithm of the radon measurement in house \(i\).
  • \(\alpha\) is the mean of the logarithm of radon measurements in all houses across all counties.
  • \(\sigma^2\) is the variance of the error. It measures the variability in the deviations of the radon levels in all the houses from the grand mean.

No-pooling Regression

\[y_{i} = \sum_{k = 1}^{85} \gamma_k (county)_k + \epsilon_{i}\] \[\epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2)\]

  • \(y_i\) is the logarithm of the radon measurement in house \(i\).
  • \(\gamma_k\) is the mean of the logarithm of radon measurements in all houses in county \(k\).
  • \(\sigma^2\) is the variance of the error. It measures the variability in the deviations of the radon levels in the houses in a county from the mean radon level of the county. 

M2 <- lm(logRadon ~ county - 1, data = radonDataset)
summary(M2)


M2 <- lm(logRadon ~ county - 1, data = radonDataset)

Multilevel Model

\[y_{i} = \alpha_{j[i]} + \epsilon_{i}\] \[\alpha_j \sim N(\mu_{\alpha}, \sigma_{\alpha}^2)\] \[\epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma_y^2)\]

This is a varying-intercept model with no predictors. It is also simply called random intercepts model or unconditional means model.

  • \(y_i\) is the logarithm of the radon measurement in house \(i\).
  • \(\alpha_{j[i]}\) is a random effect of county \(j\). It is the mean of the logarithm of radon measurements in all houses in county \(j\).
  • \(\mu_{\alpha}\) is the mean of the logarithm of radon measurements in all houses across all counties.
  • \(\sigma_{\alpha}^2\) is the variance between counties.
  • \(\sigma_{y}^2\) is the variance within a county.

Model with a Unit-Level Predictor 

floorDataset <- read.table("srrs2.dat", header = T, sep = ",")
floorDataset <- dplyr::select(floorDataset, idnum, state, floor) %>%
                filter(state == "MN") %>%
                dplyr::select(-state)
radonDataset <- merge(radonDataset, floorDataset)

9   5089  ANOKA        3 -0.3566749     0
10  5090  ANOKA        3  0.1823216     0

Complete-pooling Regression

\[y_{i} = \alpha + \beta (floor)_i + \epsilon_{i}\] \[\epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2)\]

  • \(y_i\) is the logarithm of the radon measurement in house \(i\).
  • \(\alpha\) is the mean of the logarithm of radon measurements that are taken at the basement.
  • \(\beta\) is the average difference between the logarithm of radon measurements taken on the first floor and the logarithm of radon measurements taken at the basement.
  • \(\sigma^2\) is the variance of the error.

No-pooling Regression

\[y_{i} = \beta (floor)_i + \sum_{k = 1}^{85} \gamma_k (county)_k + \epsilon_{i}\] \[\epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2)\]

  • \(y_i\) is the logarithm of the radon measurement in house \(i\).
  • \(\beta\) is the average difference between the logarithm of radon measurements taken on the first floor and the logarithm of radon measurements taken at the basement.
  • \(\gamma_k\) is the mean of the logarithm of radon measurements taken at the basement in all houses in county \(k\).
  • \(\sigma^2\) is the variance of the error.

Multilevel Model

\[y_{i} = \alpha_{j[i]} + \beta (floor)_i + \epsilon_{i}\] \[\alpha_j \sim N(\mu_{\alpha}, \sigma_{\alpha}^2)\] \[\epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma_y^2)\]

This is a varying-intercept model with a unit-level predictor.

  • \(y_i\) is the logarithm of the radon measurement in house \(i\).
  • \(\alpha_{j[i]}\) is a random effect of county \(j\). It is the mean of the logarithm of radon measurements taken at the basement in all houses in county \(j\).
  • \(\beta\) is the average difference between the logarithm of radon measurements taken on the first floor and the logarithm of radon measurements taken at the basement.
  • \(\mu_{\alpha}\) is the mean of the logarithm of radon measurements taken at the basement in all houses across all counties.
  • \(\sigma_{\alpha}^2\) is the variance between counties.
  • \(\sigma_{y}^2\) is the variance within a county.

Multilevel Model

\[y_{i} = \alpha_{j[i]} + \beta_{j[i]} (floor)_i + \epsilon_{i}\] \[\alpha_j \sim N(\mu_{\alpha}, \sigma_{\alpha}^2)\] \[\beta_j \sim N(\mu_{\beta}, \sigma_{\beta}^2)\] \[\epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma_y^2)\]

This is a varying-intercept, varying slope model.

  • \(y_i\) is the logarithm of the radon measurement in house \(i\).
  • \(\alpha_{j[i]}\) is a random effect of county \(j\). It is the mean of the logarithm of radon measurements taken at the basement in all houses in county \(j\).
  • \(\beta_{j[i]}\) is another random effect of county \(j\). It is the average difference between the logarithm of radon measurements taken on the first floor and the logarithm of radon measurements taken at the basement in all houses in county \(j\).
  • \(\mu_{\alpha}\) is the mean of the logarithm of radon measurements taken at the basement in all houses across all counties.
  • \(\mu_{\beta}\) is the mean of the difference between the logarithm of radon measurements taken on the first floor and the logarithm of radon measurements taken at the basement in all houses across all counties.
  • \(\sigma_{\alpha}^2\) and \(\sigma_{\beta}^2\) are variances between counties.
  • \(\sigma_{y}^2\) is the variance within a county.
